english:
  title: Record of the Renovation of Kangjangam Hermitage on Tudu Mountain
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the autumn of the third year of Zhizhi, my friend Lee Deok-yu came to me and spoke of his ancestor, the venerable Master Dongan, who served King Chungnyeol during the Zhiyuan era as a Remonstrance Official. Though his words went unheeded and he resigned his post, he cherished the hills and streams of Samcheok County, his ancestral home. There he journeyed to the foot of Tudu Mountain to spend his final years.

    From youth, the Master devoted himself to scholarship—there was no field of learning he did not penetrate. Yet his nature inclined toward the Buddha, and in his later years his devotion deepened. He built a separate villa, naming it the Hall of Peaceful Repose, and there he dwelt. At the nearby Samhwa Temple, he borrowed the Buddhist scriptures and spent ten years reading through them carefully, day after day. Afterward, he donated the villa to the monks and renamed it the Hermitage of Scriptural Contemplation, also gifting nearby fields to ensure its perpetual support.

    Twenty-four years have passed since the Master's passing. I myself, holding a minor office, dwell far from home, yet memories of him visit me in both sleep and waking. Last year, my middle brother, who has left the world to study the Buddha's way, returned to our native place to see our mother. There he found the hermitage crumbling with age, its timbers rotting and its walls collapsing. He sighed and said: "This was built with our father's own care and intention. How can I, now a monk, bear to watch it fall to ruin?" He then appealed to our eldest brother, and together with his disciples, they undertook its restoration.

    Our luck was great, for the inspector of the Eastern Provinces, a man of cultivated taste and generous spirit, heard of the work and sent official support to complete what the brothers could not achieve alone. In less than a year, the reconstruction was finished.

    Originally, the Master's vision was one of simplicity and restraint—he desired no ornament. The hermitage's structure was modest, designed merely to keep out wind and rain, embodying the spirit of Tao Yuanming's "a space that just fits" and "an ease that asks for nothing more." But when the work was complete, my brothers reflected: "Though our father lived by humble virtues, this place has become a shrine to his memory. Should we not enhance its dignity?" So they enlarged the proportions, widened the galleries and columns, added brilliant colors and delicate paintings—a transformation far more lavish than before.

    On the day of completion, my brothers rejoiced and said: "The hermitage is renewed. We should have an inscription written for it." They wrote to me: "You have wandered far and could not labor with us on this work. Yet if you could petition the great writers of our age for even a single inscription that might illuminate why our father built this place and why we have restored it—something that will endure and not fade—then you would honor your parents and brothers. We ask this of you."

    I reflected that I could not leave my ancestor's deeds unrecorded, nor could I ignore my brothers' request. And so I turn to you, my friend, who knows these matters well. Let me share what I have observed:

    I see that throughout the realm, Buddhism is revered excessively. Temples and pagodas line every road where merchants travel. The monks cluster around the powerful and wealthy, poisoning the people and treating scholars like servants. This is why our tradition does not embrace such excess. Yet is this truly Buddhism's fault? The Buddha teaches goodness and rejects harm. When we examine his teaching of illuminating the mind and revealing one's true nature, it seems rooted in the very principles we scholars uphold. Wise men and noble souls have found profound meaning in such teachings and do not abandon them without reason.

    Regarding the Master's life: his deeds are recorded in family annals and official histories; his name lives in common speech. His integrity in advancing and withdrawing from office is beyond question. In retirement, he never forgot his sovereign for a moment. When called to serve, he found no peace in his position. When duty called, he showed courage that knew no equal. When profit beckoned, he feigned weakness. His steadfast practice never wavered—not the shallow artifice of one seeking fame and swaying crowds.

    Had his counsel been heeded, our people's suffering might have ceased and their prosperity flourished. Even unused, the lingering influence of his virtue has the power to make the callous compassionate and the weak resolute. His contribution to the moral order is not slight.

    Considered thus, today's renovation is merely a small matter attended to in leisure. Yet how could a filial son stand unmoved before such a place, watching it crumble? As surely as autumn frost and spring dew stir our hearts, so too must the dwelling of the heart's repose be preserved and honored. It is fitting that my brothers labored diligently and that their younger brother earnestly sought this record.

    The Master's name was Seung-hyu, his courtesy name Hyu-hyu, and Dongan was his chosen epithet. In the early years of the Dade era, he was summoned to court but earnestly requested to return to the mountains, whereupon he retired as Vice-Director of the Secretariat with the rank of Attendant Lord. His eldest son, Imjong, passed the examinations and served with renown for integrity and capability, rising to the position of Minister of Justice before retiring to care for his mother in our homeland. His second son took monastic vows as Tamuk, passed the highest examination at the Jogye Monastery selection, and became a master of the Zen tradition. Deok-yu, the youngest, once competed with me in the examinations of the Gyemyo year and now serves as Drafter of Decrees. People praise the learning and virtue of his family line.
